			<h6 class="text-header">Genius is going places</h6>
      The way I see it, Genius is croud-sourcing culture - like a modern, open-source, and incredibly relevant Wikipedia. Being able to literally "annotate the world" is an increasingly possible feat with the advent of technologies such as Google Glass, an idea that postively eclipses Yelp in terms of reach (you could annotate restaurants, sure, but how about apartment buildings? Public parks? Car dealerships?). I see Spotify lyrics containing Genius annotations, political debates fact-checked <em>live</em> by enthusiastic Genius users, and entire books annotated by their authors.
      <br>
      <br>
      What if Github code comments used a more elegant system...maybe one like Genius? And imagine how easily the philosophy behind Genius could apply to education - instead of printing out 50 pages of a book to annotate, students could collaborate online (think Google Docs), professors could upload their annotated textbooks for students to study (think SparkNotes). I believe that Genius could start a revolution that alters the manner in which society communicates, and I want nothing more than to be a part of that.
